You @nsitharaman could have made long term capital gains tax rate 20% with indexation for all asset classes. That is the real simplification and equal treatment. Inflation ravages the value of money. Let us say, an equity fund has delivered 12% annualised returns over 10 years. Assume the inflation is 6% for the same period. The real value of capital appreciation is only 6% (12%- 6%). By taxing the entire 12% gains at 12.5%, the actual tax paid on real gains (6%) is very much higher.

text:
I’m 100% in support of adults pursuing whatever gender they please, by whatever means they like. 

More power to you! 

However, we will look back at this time, when doctors and “professionals” pressured parents to perform surgery and give hormones to *children*, with great shame and regret.  

The detransition stories are just starting, and they are devastating. 

These stories always include the parents and children being bullied into making irreversible decisions.

They make decisions they don’t fully understand but are told will solve a complex problem. However, in most cases, this “problem” is solved best with love, compassion, counseling, and time. 

Adolescence is challenging 100% of the time, as we all have experienced. 

Imagine your darkest and most confusing moment as a teenager. Now, imagine a group of authorities telling you that your gender confusion causes all your pain and that you can solve all of that pain with surgery and hormones. 

Now imagine the state of California acting to hide this child’s struggle from their parents — and then pursuing a gender transition covertly with the child. 

That is the crime that is happening right now. 

We don’t let kids smoke vapes or drink until they are fully informed of the ramifications of those decisions as adults  — yet we put them on puberty blockers and have them do surgery to change their gender as teenagers? 

What is the rush? 

There isn’t one, so they tell the parents, “Your child will kill themselves if they don’t transition.”

This is pure evil. 

There are no parents who agree with this, there are only bullied and confused parents… and that needs to end now. 

I say this with unlimited compassion and love for any child or family dealing with gender dysphoria. 

Please speak up parents.

text:
Buckle up: Happy $TSLA earnings day. Here are my 5 focus areas ranked by importance:

1) Timing of new vehicle ramp. Commentary related on when to expect ramping of new models that will be announced at the October event. Last quarter Elon expected these new models to “start of production in the second half of 2025.” The reason why this is the most important topic is these new models will both accelerate delivery growth and pave the way for higher margin FSD and fleet revenue. 

Side note: currently, the Street is expecting for around 15% delivery growth in CY25. This number will be dramatically impacted by the timing of the ramp of these new models. I suspect by 2026 at least one model will be ramping which should yield delivery growth in CY26 of +20%.

2) Incremental FSD miles driven. This number is going to skyrocket given V12, which came out in March. By April 23, V12 had logged over 300m miles. Extrapolating that for the balance of the June quarter suggests they added around 950m miles, which would imply 95% q/q growth, compared to 19% q/q in Dec-23. Separately, on April 5, Elon posted that it “won’t be long until Tesla exceeds 10B miles of FSD.”

3) Auto gross margins ex credits. Historically, this metric has been the focal point of Tesla’s earnings. This quarter it drops to the 3rd most important factor given near-term profitability is less important than the long-term profitability once new models and FSD ramp in 2026 and beyond. While its importance is diminished on this earnings, it’s still important. FactSet reports consensus at 16.9% compared to 16.4% in Mar-24. I believe any number above 16% will satisfy investors. In other words, as long as margins hang in there, the story is intact.

5) China. China accounts for about 30% of total vehicle revenue and has been under slight competitive pressures, as evidenced by Market share of Tesla vehicles in China decreasing from 2.3 to 2.2% from the December quarter to March quarter. Last quarter, the takeaway from the China business was Elon’s confidence for FSD approval. I’m most interested in any progress in the relationship with Baidu and FSD given advancements in that partnership increase the probability that Tesla will have autonomous success in China down the road.

6) Politics. Musk’s recent endorsement of Trump and commitment to donate $45m/mo to his campaign poses two new questions around the Tesla story. First, what is he hoping to achieve with a closer relationship with a Trump White House (somehow maintaining of EV tax credits, more favorable legislation related to autonomy)? Second, is Musk entertaining political ambitions in the form of a presidential appointment or potentially greater political ambitions? This of course will be viewed as negative to investors as it would take time away from Tesla. As a reminder, Musk is ineligible for US presidency given he was born outside of the US. He could run for Congress or more likely governor of Texas. I put the odds at less than 10% that Musk wants a future in politics given the world of politics is filled with red tape that goes against his first principles approach to life.

1. No of people who pay income tax (pay, not file) is 2% or lower of the population. At most 2%. Even if you include dependents it is very, very comfortably less than 10%.

2. A much larger number of people pay GST, but that is mostly covered by GST council and less by Union Budget. Similarly for state taxes. GST rates have been cut compared to pre-GST equivalent rates.

3. Entry-level income tax payment was again reduced this year as exemption was increased (including on capital gains.) An argument can be made that is keeping up with inflation, but again entry level income tax payment starts in India from 4x the per capita income (in America, it is 1/4th per capita income.)

4. People on Twitter are not representative of Indian public. Like it or not, we have universal adult franchise - I support universal adult franchise by the way. Same dynamic has to be accepted in caste/quote debates.

5. "Middle class" is far, far from the median class of India. It is more like 90 percentile plus. If you have a college degree, have/had a formal job and are spending time on Twitter - you are far from 50 percentile.

6. Logically, such a sliver cannot be the "core" base of any political party that actually wants to win elections though of course given English MSM/SM - this class sets the narrative.

7. Who is left? Farmers and non-salaried small businesses. Latter is being slowly but surely forcibly formalised, former the government tried using its political capital for now. 

8. What about the super-rich? This government raised capital gains rate (LT and ST), STT, dividend taxes - one cannot say that it is in anyway helping the rich.
